      { id:"mediocre", label:"Response B", badge:"OK",
        text:"Gradient descent is an iterative optimisation algorithm that minimises a differentiable function by moving in the direction of steepest descent. For a loss function J(θ), the update rule is:\n\n    θ = θ − α ∇J(θ)\n\nwhere α is the learning rate and ∇J(θ) is the gradient of the loss with respect to parameters θ. This is repeated until convergence." },
      { id:"bad", label:"Response C", badge:"Poor",
        text:"Gradient descent is how neural networks learn by climbing up the gradient to reach the maximum point. The algorithm increases the loss function using backpropagation. By going up the gradient, the model finds better weights. You repeat this until the loss is at its highest, which means the model is fully trained." }
    ],
    judgements:{
